node.text: Russian cosmonauts Oleg Novitskiy and Pyotr Dubrov of Roscosmos concluded their spacewalk today at 6:16 p.m. EDT after 7 hours and 25 minutes. It was the second of up to 11 spacewalks to prepare the new Nauka multipurpose laboratory module for operations in space.

node.title: Cosmonauts Wrap Up Second Spacewalk to Set Up Science Module

node.text: The SpaceX Cargo Dragon arrived at the station 30 minutes early on Monday docking to the Harmony module's forward port at 10:30 a.m. EDT. Some of the new science experiments will explore radioactivity's affects on bone tissue, study astronaut vision issues, demonstrate robotic crew support, and ways to genetically engineer plants in space.

node.title: Cargo Dragon Delivers New Science and Supplies

node.text:
The astronauts aboard the International Space Station are ready for a big shipment of science experiments and supplies. From seeds to a robotic arm, @astro.megan and @astro_kimbrough will soon welcome research that launched early this morning aboard SpaceX’s 23rd commercial resupply mission to station.
 
#science #space #astronaut #ISS #SpaceStation #research #spacex

node.text: The Cargo Dragon spacecraft successfully launched on the SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket on Sunday at 3:14 a.m. EDT from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida. It will deliver more than 4,800 pounds of research, crew supplies and hardware to the International Space Station when docks on Monday at about 11 a.m.

node.text:
Experiments aboard the 23rd SpaceX Commercial Resupply Mission to the International Space Station include an investigation of protecting bone health with botanical byproducts, testing a way to monitor crew eye health, demonstrating improved dexterity of robots, exposing materials to the harsh environment of space, mitigating stress in plants, and more.

#space #science #research #spacestation #robotics #iss #nasa

node.title: Bone, plant and materials studies are ready for lift off!

node.text: Experiments that demonstrate 3D printing with dust, use engineered tissue to study muscle loss, and analyze growth of slime mold, along with other scientific studies and supplies, are headed to the International Space Station on Northrop Grumman’s 16th commercial resupply services mission (NG CRS-16). Launch of the Cygnus spacecraft is targeted for August 10 from NASA’s Wallops Flight Facility in Virginia.

node.title: 3D Printing, Muscle Cells, and Mold Experiments Launching to Space Station

node.text: This morning at 6:55 a.m. EDT the Pirs docking compartment, with the attached Progress 77 spacecraft, separated from the Space Station that had been its home for the past 20 years. #nasa #roscosmos #pirs #progress77 #progress #spacestation

node.text: The SpaceX Crew Dragon Endeavour, with Crew-2 astronauts aboard, undocked from Harmony's forward-facing port at 6:45am ET and relocated to the space-facing port to re-docked to the station 7:35 am ET, completing the second space station port change for the crewed spacecraft.

node.text: The SpaceX Cargo Dragon undocked from the space station today at 10:45 a.m. EDT. Astronaut Shane Kimbrough thanked the ground crews that supported Cargo Dragon operations as the U.S. spacecraft headed to the Gulf of Mexico for a splashdown on Friday.

node.title: Astronaut Shane Kimbrough Thanks Cargo Dragon Operations Personnel

node.text: Russian cosmonauts Oleg Novitskiy and Pyotr Dubrov of Roscosmos concluded their spacewalk today at 6:16 p.m. EDT after 7 hours and 25 minutes. It was the second of up to 11 spacewalks to prepare the new Nauka multipurpose laboratory module for operations in space.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by International Space Station on September 08, 2021 tagging @roscosmosofficial, and @novitskiy_iss.

node.text:
(Pics 1 and 2) Russian spacewalkers Oleg Novitskiy and Pyotr Dubrov, pictured here on Sept. 3, will exit the station’s Poisk airlock on Thursday at 11 a.m. EDT to continue outfitting the Nauka multipurpose laboratory module for science operations live on NASA TV (link in profile). In pics 3 and 4, cosmonaut Pyotr Dubrov works to configure Nauka on Sept. 3. In pic 5, the Nauka module is pictured as the station orbited into a sunset above the southern Indian Ocean.

#roscosmos #cosmonaut #walk #spacewalk #suit #spacesuit #nauka #earth #sunset #southern #indian #ocean

node.text: The SpaceX Cargo Dragon arrived at the station 30 minutes early on Monday docking to the Harmony module's forward port at 10:30 a.m. EDT. Some of the new science experiments will explore radioactivity's affects on bone tissue, study astronaut vision issues, demonstrate robotic crew support, and ways to genetically engineer plants in space.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by International Space Station on August 29, 2021 tagging @spacex, @nasa, and @nasakennedy. May be an image of outdoors.

node.text:
NASA TV (link in profile) begins its live coverage on Monday at 9:30 a.m. EDT of the SpaceX Cargo Dragon arriving at the station. It will autonomously dock to the Harmony module's forward port at 11 a.m. Pictured here is the SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket launching the Cargo Dragon spacecraft from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center into Earth orbit on Sunday at 3:14 a.m. Credit: SpaceX

node.text:
The astronauts aboard the International Space Station are ready for a big shipment of science experiments and supplies. From seeds to a robotic arm, @astro.megan and @astro_kimbrough will soon welcome research that launched early this morning aboard SpaceX’s 23rd commercial resupply mission to station.
 
#science #space #astronaut #ISS #SpaceStation #research #spacex

node.text: The Cargo Dragon spacecraft successfully launched on the SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket on Sunday at 3:14 a.m. EDT from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center in Florida. It will deliver more than 4,800 pounds of research, crew supplies and hardware to the International Space Station when docks on Monday at about 11 a.m.

node.accessibility_caption: Photo shared by International Space Station on August 27, 2021 tagging @nasa, @astro_kimbrough, @nasaastronauts, and @astro.megan. May be an image of 2 people, people sitting and indoor.

node.text: NASA Flight Engineers Shane Kimbrough and Megan McArthur will be on duty Sunday monitoring the SpaceX Cargo Dragon when it autonomously docks at 11 a.m. EDT to the Harmony module’s forward international docking adapter. The Cargo Dragon will launch atop the SpaceX Falcon 9 rocket on Saturday at 3:37 a.m. from NASA’s Kennedy Space Center with over 4,800 pounds of new science experiments, crew supplies and lab hardware. #nasa #astronaut #spacex #cargo #dragon #cargodragon #international #space #station

node.text:
🤖 Imagine free-flying robots performing satellite servicing or building large space structures.
👁️ See some preliminary work getting us closer to this right now aboard the International Space Station. The Astrobee ReSwarm project is working on the maneuverability of the Astrobee robots in space.
👂 You can even hear the impellers pulling in air and the steerable nozzles flipping open and closed!

node.text:
The Falcon 9 rocket from SpaceX with the Cargo Dragon spacecraft atop is standing vertical at its launch pad at the Kennedy Space Center in Florida today. It is scheduled to launch on Saturday at 3:37 a.m. EDT and arrive at the station on Sunday for an autonomous docking at 11 a.m. Flight Engineers Megan McArthur and Shane Kimbrough will be on duty Sunday morning monitoring Dragon’s rendezvous and docking to the Harmony module’s forward international docking adapter. NASA TV will broadcast both launch and docking events live. Credit: SpaceX
